6-01-19 02:17:05','<strong>Training</strong> is the first step to get involved with the ILCM Pro Bono Project<em>. </em>\r\n\r\nRegistrations and training sign ups are available below.','Trainings and Registration','','publish','closed','closed','','trainings-and-registration','','','2016-03-17 02:40:12','2016-03-17 02:40:12','',254,'http://localhost:8888/?page_id=274',0,'page','',0),(275,1,'2016-01-19 02:17:05','2016-01-19 02:17:05','asdf','Trainings and Registration','','inherit','closed','closed','','274-revision-v1','','','2016-01-19 02:17:05','2016-01-19 02:17:05','',274,'http://localhost:8888/274-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(276,1,'2016-01-19 02:18:06','2016-01-19 02:18:06',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','276','','','2016-01-25 04:14:24','2016-01-25 04:14:24','',254,'http://localhost:8888/?p=276',5,'nav_menu_item','',0),(277,1,'2016-01-19 02:20:36','2016-01-19 02:20:36','<p align=\"left\">ILCM\'s partnerships with law firms and private attorneys provide low-income immigrants and their families with legal assistance, give attorneys a unique professional development opportunity coupled with a chance to give to those in need, and allow us to give aid to an even greater number of people.</p>\r\nPro bono attorneys can earn Continuing Legal Education (CLE) credits by representing our clients. Please visit the <a href=\"http://www.mbcle.state.mn.us/MBCLE/PAGES/PROBONO.ASP\" target=\"_blank\">Minnesota Board of Continuing Legal Education\'s website</a> for more information.\r\n\r\n<strong>Casework resources</strong> are available for registered pro bono attorneys. Please see Login on the right side of the page.\r\n<h2 class=\"art-postheader\">Pro Bono Projects</h2>\r\nILCM’s Pro Bono Project trains and coordinates volunteer attorneys and other legal professionals to represent clients in high-demand areas of immigration law. The Project has ongoing programs to train and mentor attorneys to provide full representation pro bono services in the areas of citizenship (N-400s and N-600s), deferred action (DACA and DACA Renewal), and Crime Victim Relief Work (U Visas and U Visa Adjustments). ILCM also coordinates brief service pro bono efforts on an as-need basis in areas of crisis or high demand, such as TPS clinics and rural outreach clinics. Throughout all of its focus areas, the Pro Bono Project strives to provide high-quality training and skills development to members of the private bar, while simultaneously increasing ILCM’s ability to serve clients.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Citizenship: </span></b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Through our Naturalization Project and Citizenship for Children Projects volunteer attorneys and paralegals can assist clients reach citizenship, the final step in their immigration process. Volunteers work with clients to conduct legal screenings, prepare the citizenship application, and accompany them to the citizenship interview.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Crime Victim Relief Work:</span></b> <span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">ILCM continues to provide full representation pro bono services for U Visa casework; helping victims of domestic violence, sexual assault, and other serious crimes obtain immigration status and a pathway to empowerment and safety. Also,  following the successful launch of a U Visa Adjustment pilot project in 2015, the Pro Bono Project now also provides full representation pro bono services to U Visa holders seeking a green card. Working with these clients, volunteers assist crime victims reach the next step toward citizenship.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">DREAMer Project:</span></b><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> Through the DREAMer Project ILCM provides trains and mentors pro bono attorneys to assist immigrant youth obtain deferred action and work authorization through the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) program. This allows young clients to come out of the shadows and gain new opportunities for success in America. The Pro Bono Project also recently initiated regular full representation clinics for DACA Renewal, where volunteers attend a brief training directly followed by a client meeting where the attorney can assist DACA holders renew their deferred action and work card. This model provides efficient service to clients while still guaranteeing the high-quality assistance that comes with full representation.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Minnesota Children &amp; Families Immigration Court Project:</span></b><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> This project is a joint effort between ILCM, Mid-Minnesota Legal Aid, the Advocates for Human Rights, and area law schools. Through this project, ILCM and its partners, recruit, train and supervise volunteers lawyers and law students to provide legal screenings to Central American Refugees who are in removal proceedings here in Minnesota. This project provides an invaluable service to highly vulnerable clients, and helps to route clients to free legal services for their deportation proceedings.  </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Connect Minnesota (Rural Minnesota Outreach): </span></b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In order to better serve immigrant and refugee clients in rural Minnesota, the Pro Bono Project is working to institute video conferencing legal advice and brief service clinics across out-state Minnesota. A pilot clinic is currently being organized in Pelican Rapids, Minnesota, to provide immigration advice and representation to immigrants and refugees residing in NW Minnesota, an area currently extremely underserved by low-cost immigration services. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Executive Action and Expansion of Deferred Action:</span></b><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> The Pro Bono Project is positioned to assist with the surge in demand for services that is expected under the November 2014 executive action of President Obama. Under that order undocumented parents of Lawful Permanent Residents and citizens will be able, in certain circumstances, to obtain deferred action and work authorization in the United States. Filing of applications for the new proposed programs are currently on hold due to a Texas Federal District Court’s injunction. However, ILCM has spent 2015 conducting information sessions to the immigrant community on eligibility and preparation for these programs, once they are implemented. Once the new categories of protections are finalized, ILCM is committed to providing pro bono programing to assist applicants.  </span></p>\r\n<em>If a friend of family member is being held in immigration custody, an attorney from this project will provide a free consultation at the immigration court prior to his or her first hearing. Although we cannot guarantee this service (due to the rising number of detainees), program staff makes every effort to meet with all detainees. There is no need to call our office to receive this service. The attorneys will be at court.</em>','Pro Bono','','inherit','closed','closed','','254-revision-v1','','','2016-01-19 02:20:36','2016-01-19 02:20:36','',254,'http://localhost:8888/254-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(278,1,'2016-01-19 02:21:40','2016-01-19 02:21:40','<p align=\"left\">ILCM\'s partnerships with law firms and private attorneys provide low-income immigrants and their families with legal assistance, give attorneys a unique professional development opportunity coupled with a chance to give to those in need, and allow us to give aid to an even greater number of people.</p>\r\nPro bono attorneys can earn Continuing Legal Education (CLE) credits by representing our clients. Please visit the <a href=\"http://www.mbcle.state.mn.us/MBCLE/PAGES/PROBONO.ASP\" target=\"_blank\">Minnesota Board of Continuing Legal Education\'s website</a> for more information.\r\n\r\n<strong>Casework resources</strong> are available for