regarding the law.</li>\r\n	<li>Reform should include a simple and timely approach to the future flow of immigrants, including permanent and temporary status. New rules should allow sufficient immigration to meet the needs of all industries (including agriculture) as well as large and small businesses alike and afford workers all protections under current laws.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLinks to other immigration reform principles:','Reform Principles','','inherit','closed','closed','','306-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 01:48:24','2016-01-25 01:48:24','',306,'http://localhost:8888/306-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(308,1,'2016-01-25 01:52:57','2016-01-25 01:52:57','The Immigrant Law Center engages passionate staff, volunteers, and community advocates to monitor and communicate pertinent legislation regarding immigration.\r\n<h2>Reform Principles</h2>\r\nThe Immigrant Law Center of Minnesota supports comprehensive immigration reform that recognizes the needs of our economy; protects security; and is humane.\r\n\r\nIn coalition with other businesses and nonprofit organizations, our Immigration Joint Policy is as follows (more information on the issue and the coalition partners can be found <strong><a href=\"https://ilcm.org/advocacy/MinnesotaBusinessAdvocacyImmigrationCoalition.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"alternate\">here</a></strong>).\r\n\r\nGoal: We support comprehensive federal reform that recognizes the needs of our economy; protects national security; and is humane.  Successful reform will modify immigration policies without creating more obstacles for workers to connect with employers and vice versa. Thus, the following must occur <em>simultaneously</em>:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Reform should include a timely and affordable way for current immigrants and their families, regardless of status, to become documented legal participants in our society. Successful businesses require stable families and communities. We support a path to permanent residency for all immigrants residing in the United States who are not otherwise excludable for reasons such as criminal convictions. We also support a timely reduction of backlogs where families and professional workers have been waiting to immigrate for many years.</li>\r\n	<li>Reform should include a simple and accurate status verification that is affordable and accessible, especially so for small businesses. Reforms should protect workers and employers who act in good faith regarding the law.</li>\r\n	<li>Reform should include a simple and timely approach to the future flow of immigrants, including permanent and temporary status. New rules should allow sufficient immigration to meet the needs of all industries (including agriculture) as well as large and small businesses alike and afford workers all protections under current laws.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Links to other immigration reform principles:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://reformimmigrationforamerica.org/blog/uncategorized/item/52-37principles.html\" target=\"_blank\">Reform Immigration for America</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.immigrationworksusa.org/uploaded/file/AILA%20Position%20Statement%20on%20Business%20Immigration%20Reform%20Principles.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">AILA Position Statement on Business Immigration Reform Principles</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.communitychange.org/need-immigration-reform-now/\" target=\"_blank\">Center for Community Change</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Advocacy','','inherit','closed','closed','','299-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 01:52:57','2016-01-25 01:52:57','',299,'http://localhost:8888/299-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(309,1,'2016-01-25 01:54:13','2016-01-25 01:54:13','ILCM occupies a unique niche among nonprofit immigration legal service providers because of the breadth of its services and service area, as well as its ability to work with clients of all nationalities. Our three-pronged model—direct legal services, education, and advocacy—allows us to comprehensively respond to and prevent immigration legal problems.\r\n\r\nOur efforts are focused on these projects and programs.','Projects','','inherit','closed','closed','','297-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 01:54:13','2016-01-25 01:54:13','',297,'http://localhost:8888/297-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(310,1,'2016-01-25 01:55:21','2016-01-25 01:55:21','ILCM occupies a unique niche among nonprofit immigration legal service providers because of the breadth of its services and service area, as well as its ability to work with clients of all nationalities. Our three-pronged model—direct legal services, education, and advocacy—allows us to comprehensively respond to and prevent immigration legal problems.\n\nOur efforts are focused on these projects and programs.\n<h2>Public Defender Project</h2>\nThe Public Defender Project provides technical assistance, training, and education to Minnesota\'s public defenders on the immigration consequences of criminal convictions for non citizen defendants in order to avoid ineffective assistance of counsel claims for public defenders, and to reduce future need for post-conviction relief petitions based on ineffective assistance of counsel.\n\n&nbsp;','Projects','','inherit','closed','closed','','297-autosave-v1','','','2016-01-25 01:55:21','2016-01-25 01:55:21','',297,'http://localhost:8888/297-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(311,1,'2016-01-25 01:56:33','2016-01-25 01:56:33','ILCM occupies a unique niche among nonprofit immigration legal service providers because of the breadth of its services and service area, as well as its ability to work with clients of all nationalities. Our three-pronged model—direct legal services, education, and advocacy—allows us to comprehensively respond to and prevent immigration legal problems.\r\n\r\nOur efforts are focused on these projects and programs.\r\n<h2>Public Defender Project</h2>\r\nThe Public Defender Project provides technical assistance, training, and education to Minnesota\'s public defenders on the immigration consequences of criminal convictions for non citizen defendants in order to avoid ineffective assistance of counsel claims for public defenders, and to reduce future need for post-conviction relief petitions based on ineffective assistance of counsel.\r\n<h2>Refugee Project</h2>\r\nThe Refugee Project helps refugees and asylees obtain their green card, along with assistance in obtaining citizenship through naturalization.\r\n<h2>Advocacy and Defense Project</h2>\r\nThe Advocacy and Defense Project combats misconceptions so that immigrant communities and the general public have the information they need to advocate for humane, fact-based, and pragmatic immigration laws and policies.\r\n\r\nRural Immigration Project','Projects','','inherit','closed','closed','','297-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 01:56:33','2016-01-25 01:56:33','',297,'http://localhost:8888/297-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(312,1,'2016-01-25 01:58:07','2016-01-25 01:58:07','The Rural Immigration Project provides legal representation and education to immigrant individuals and families living in rural Minnesota, primarily in the southwestern area.\r\n\r\nWhile the bulk of ILCM’s clients (approximately 54 percent) reside in Ramsey, Dakota, and Washington counties, ILCM traditionally only provided comprehensive services to residents of Ramsey and the 32 counties of southern Minnesota. ILCM only served residents of all other Minnesota counties through statewide projects that focused on providing immigration services to persons who had been victims of domestic violence or other serious crimes, and persons who were in detention. However, recognizing the need for services throughout Minnesota, ILCM’s board voted in 2009 to extend our services to Minneapolis and throughout the State of Minnesota. ILCM opened a full-time office in Worthington in December 2009 and for the first time since ILCM was created in 1996, ILCM is working to meet the overall legal service needs of the entire statewide immigrant community.','Rural Immigration Project','','publish','closed','closed','','rural-immigration-project','','','2016-01-25 01:58:07','2016-01-25 01:58:07','',297,'http://localhost:8888/?page_id=312',0,'page','',0),(313,1,'2016-01-25 01:58:07','2016-01-25 01:58:07','The Rural Immigration Project provides legal representation and education to immigrant individuals and families living in rural Minnesota, primarily in the southwestern area.\r\n\r\nWhile the bulk of ILCM’s clients (approximately 54 percent) reside in Ramsey, Dakota, and Washington counties, ILCM traditionally only provided comprehensive services to residents of Ramsey and the 32 counties of southern Minnesota. ILCM only served residents of all other Minnesota counties through statewide projects that focused on providing immigration services to persons who had been victims of domestic violence or other serious crimes, and persons who were in detention. However, recognizing the need for services throughout Minnesota, ILCM’s board voted in 2009 to extend our services to Minneapolis and throughout the State of Minnesota. ILCM opened a full-time office in Worthington in December 2009 and for the first time since ILCM was created in 1996, ILCM is working to meet the overall legal service needs of the entire statewide immigrant community.','Rural Immigration Project','','inherit','closed','closed','','312-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 01:58:07','2016-01-25 01:58:07','',312,'http://localhost:8888/312-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(314,1,'2016-01-25 02:03:48','2016-01-25 02:03:48',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','314','','','2016-02-28 22:14:12','2016-02-28 22:14:12','',297,'http://localhost:8888/?p=314',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(315,1,'2016-01-25 02:03:49','2016-01-25 02:03:49',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','315','','','2016-02-28 22:14:12','2016-02-28 22:14:12','',299,'http://localhost:8888/?p=315',6,'nav_menu_item','',0),(316,1,'2016-01-25 04:02:39','2016-01-25 04:02:39','Immigrants and refugees are undoubtedly invaluable to the State of Minnesota. Immigrants revitalize our rural and urban communities, starting new businesses, stopping rural and inner-core population decline, keeping school districts functioning, reestablishing a healthy tax base, and generating more resources for the entire community. The value of immigrants, however, has not translated into obvious social, cultural, or political support at the local, state, or federal levels.\r\n\r\nDespite immigrant and refugees’ positive contributions, legal and policy barriers continue to threaten their welfare and vitality. Foremost among those barriers is our current outdated and ill-equipped immigration system. Under the current system there are long lines to immigrate family members (1 ½ to 22 or more years), no means for those waiting to immigrate to obtain temporary work authorization, and for millions, no path to any legal status despite years of living in the United States, working productively, and having U.S. born children. This broken system unfortunately is met with a complete absence of action on any new, fair, and humane federal immigration plan (comprehensive immigration reform, or CIR).\r\n\r\nCIR remains the only viable, pragmatic, and ethical option for fixing the broken immigration system, which would provide a path to legalization for unauthorized immigrants, prioritize the unity and integrity of families, protect workers rights, reestablish the rule of law including creating legal and effective border crossings, and encourage civic engagement. It will not only give important rights and responsibilities to those now living in the shadows of American society, but also will meet the economic and security needs of our country and enable broken communities to grow and heal. Finally, it will bring relief to the legal immigrants and refugees who pay an immense price for anti-immigrant rhetoric fueled by impracticable policies. Efforts to portray undocumented immigrants as a threat to communal safety and prosperity have a chilling effect on the formation of important community bonds between immigrant groups and members of the general public, who are unable or unwilling to differentiate between legal and undocumented immigrants. The passage of CIR will remove a principal impetus behind anti-immigrant rhetoric, thereby fostering an environment in which all immigrants can fully integrate into their communities.\r\n\r\nILCM’s advocacy work over the last four years has educated, advocated, and led thousands of persons to try to bring about a more just environment for immigrants and refugees in Minnesota. Our work has achieved many important objectives but there is much more work we must still do.','Advocacy and Defense Project','','publish','closed','closed','','advocacy-and-defense-project','','','2016-01-25 04:02:39','2016-01-25 04:02:39','',297,'http://localhost:8888/?page_id=316',1,'page','',0),(317,1,'2016-01-25 04:02:39','2016-01-25 04:02:39','Immigrants and refugees are undoubtedly invaluable to the State of Minnesota. Immigrants revitalize our rural and urban communities, starting new businesses, stopping rural and inner-core population decline, keeping school districts functioning, reestablishing a healthy tax base, and generating more resources for the entire community. The value of immigrants, however, has not translated into obvious social, cultural, or political support at the local, state, or federal levels.\r\n\r\nDespite immigrant and refugees’ positive contributions, legal and policy barriers continue to threaten their welfare and vitality. Foremost among those barriers is our current outdated and ill-equipped immigration system. Under the current system there are long lines to immigrate family members (1 ½ to 22 or more years), no means for those waiting to immigrate to obtain temporary work authorization, and for millions, no path to any legal status despite years of living in the United States, working productively, and having U.S. born children. This broken system unfortunately is met with a complete absence of action on any new, fair, and humane federal immigration plan (comprehensive immigration reform, or CIR).\r\n\r\nCIR remains the only viable, pragmatic, and ethical option for fixing the broken immigration system, which would provide a path to legalization for unauthorized immigrants, prioritize the unity and integrity of families, protect workers rights, reestablish the rule of law including creating legal and effective border crossings, and encourage civic engagement. It will not only give important rights and responsibilities to those now living in the shadows of American society, but also will meet the economic and security needs of our country and enable broken communities to grow and heal. Finally, it will bring relief to the legal immigrants and refugees who pay an immense price for anti-immigrant rhetoric fueled by impracticable policies. Efforts to portray undocumented immigrants as a threat to communal safety and prosperity have a chilling effect on the formation of important community bonds between immigrant groups and members of the general public, who are unable or unwilling to differentiate between legal and undocumented immigrants. The passage of CIR will remove a principal impetus behind anti-immigrant rhetoric, thereby fostering an environment in which all immigrants can fully integrate into their communities.\r\n\r\nILCM’s advocacy work over the last four years has educated, advocated, and led thousands of persons to try to bring about a more just environment for immigrants and refugees in Minnesota. Our work has achieved many important objectives but there is much more work we must still do.','Advocacy and Defense Project','','inherit','closed','closed','','316-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 04:02:39','2016-01-25 04:02:39','',316,'http://localhost:8888/316-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(318,1,'2016-01-25 04:03:28','2016-01-25 04:03:28',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','318','','','2016-02-28 22:14:12','2016-02-28 22:14:12','',297,'http://localhost:8888/?p=318',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(319,1,'2016-01-25 04:04:10','2016-01-25 04:04:10','ILCM occupies a unique niche among nonprofit immigration legal service providers because of the breadth of its services and service area, as well as its ability to work with clients of all nationalities. Our three-pronged model—direct legal services, education, and advocacy—allows us to comprehensively respond to and prevent immigration legal problems.\r\n\r\nOur efforts are focused on these projects and programs.\r\n<h2>Public Defender Project</h2>\r\nThe Public Defender Project provides technical assistance, training, and education to Minnesota\'s public defenders on the immigration consequences of criminal convictions for non citizen defendants in order to avoid ineffective assistance of counsel claims for public defenders, and to reduce future need for post-conviction relief petitions based on ineffective assistance of counsel.\r\n<h2></h2>','Projects','','inherit','closed','closed','','297-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 04:04:10','2016-01-25 04:04:10','',297,'http://localhost:8888/297-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(320,1,'2016-01-25 04:09:14','2016-01-25 04:09:14','<p align=\"left\">ILCM\'s partnerships with law firms and private attorneys provide low-income immigrants and their families with legal assistance, give attorneys a unique professional development opportunity coupled with a chance to give to those in need, and allow us to give aid to an even greater number of people.</p>\r\nPro bono attorneys can earn Continuing Legal Education (CLE) credits by representing our clients. Please visit the <a href=\"http://www.mbcle.state.mn.us/MBCLE/PAGES/PROBONO.ASP\" target=\"_blank\">Minnesota Board of Continuing Legal Education\'s website</a> for more information.\r\n\r\n<strong>Casework resources</strong> are available for registered pro bono attorneys. Please see Login on the right side of the page.\r\n<h2 class=\"art-postheader\"></h2>\r\n<h2 class=\"art-postheader\">Upcoming Trainings and Registration</h2>\r\nFind out more information and register for upcoming training sessions by going to the <a href=\"http://localhost:8888/get-involved/pro-bono/trainings-and-registration/\">Trainings and Registration </a>page.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2 class=\"art-postheader\">Pro Bono Projects</h2>\r\nILCM’s Pro Bono Project trains and coordinates volunteer attorneys and other legal professionals to represent clients in high-demand areas of immigration law. The Project has ongoing programs to train and mentor attorneys to provide full representation pro bono services in the areas of citizenship (N-400s and N-600s), deferred action (DACA and DACA Renewal), and Crime Victim Relief Work (U Visas and U Visa Adjustments). ILCM also coordinates brief service pro bono efforts on an as-need basis in areas of crisis or high demand, such as TPS clinics and rural outreach clinics. Throughout all of its focus areas, the Pro Bono Project strives to provide high-quality training and skills development to members of the private bar, while simultaneously increasing ILCM’s ability to serve clients.\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Citizenship </span></b></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Through our Naturalization Project and Citizenship for Children Projects volunteer attorneys and paralegals can assist clients reach citizenship, the final step in their immigration process. Volunteers work with clients to conduct legal screenings, prepare the citizenship application, and accompany them to the citizenship interview.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Crime Victim Relief Work</span></b><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">ILCM continues to provide full representation pro bono services for U Visa casework; helping victims of domestic violence, sexual assault, and other serious crimes obtain immigration status and a pathway to empowerment and safety. Also,  following the successful launch of a U Visa Adjustment pilot project in 2015, the Pro Bono Project now also provides full representation pro bono services to U Visa holders seeking a green card. Working with these clients, volunteers assist crime victims reach the next step toward citizenship.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">DREAMer Project</span></b></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Through the DREAMer Project ILCM provides trains and mentors pro bono attorneys to assist immigrant youth obtain deferred action and work authorization through the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) program. This allows young clients to come out of the shadows and gain new opportunities for success in America. The Pro Bono Project also recently initiated regular full representation clinics for DACA Renewal, where volunteers attend a brief training directly followed by a client meeting where the attorney can assist DACA holders renew their deferred action and work card. This model provides efficient service to clients while still guaranteeing the high-quality assistance that comes with full representation.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Minnesota Children &amp; Families Immigration Court Project</span></b></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">This project is a joint effort between ILCM, Mid-Minnesota Legal Aid, the Advocates for Human Rights, and area law schools. Through this project, ILCM and its partners, recruit, train and supervise volunteers lawyers and law students to provide legal screenings to Central American Refugees who are in removal proceedings here in Minnesota. This project provides an invaluable service to highly vulnerable clients, and helps to route clients to free legal services for their deportation proceedings.  </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Connect Minnesota (Rural Minnesota Outreach)</span></b></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In order to better serve immigrant and refugee clients in rural Minnesota, the Pro Bono Project is working to institute video conferencing legal advice and brief service clinics across out-state Minnesota. A pilot clinic is currently being organized in Pelican Rapids, Minnesota, to provide immigration advice and representation to immigrants and refugees residing in NW Minnesota, an area currently extremely underserved by low-cost immigration services. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Executive Action and Expansion of Deferred Action</span></b></p>\r\n<p class=\"x_MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The Pro Bono Project is positioned to assist with the surge in demand for services that is expected under the November 2014 executive action of President Obama. Under that order undocumented parents of Lawful Permanent Residents and citizens will be able, in certain circumstances, to obtain deferred action and work authorization in the United States. Filing of applications for the new proposed programs are currently on hold due to a Texas Federal District Court’s injunction. However, ILCM has spent 2015 conducting information sessions to the immigrant community on eligibility and preparation for these programs, once they are implemented. Once the new categories of protections are finalized, ILCM is committed to providing pro bono programing to assist applicants.  </span></p>\r\n<em>If a friend of family member is being held in immigration custody, an attorney from this project will provide a free consultation at the immigration court prior to his or her first hearing. Although we cannot guarantee this service (due to the rising number of detainees), program staff makes every effort to meet with all detainees. There is no need to call our office to receive this service. The attorneys will be at court.</em>','Pro Bono','','inherit','closed','closed','','254-revision-v1','','','2016-01-25 04:09:14','2016-01-25 04:09:14','',254,'http://localhost:8888/254-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(321,1,'2016-01-25 04:11:55','2016-01-25 04:11:55','<div class=\"art-postmetadataheader\">\r\n<h2 class=\"art-postheader\">DACA Renewal Resources</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"art-postcontent clearfix\">\r\n<div class=\"art-article\">\r\n<table border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>DACA Renewal Resources</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href=\"https://ilcm.org/probono/manuals/ILCMDACARenewalManual.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"alternate\"><img src=\"https://ilcm.org/images/stories/file_icon.gif\" alt=\"[file]\" border=\"0\" /></a><a href=\"https://ilcm.org/probono/manuals/DACArenewalmanualoct2015.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"alternate\">DACA Renewal Manual</a> -- UPDATED 09/2015</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Letters to Clients</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"https://ilcm.org/images/stories/file_icon.gif\" alt=\"[file]\" border=\"0\" /><a href=\"https://ilcm.org/probono/manuals/DREAMers/FiledcaseLTclientDeferredAction.docx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"alternate\">Case Filed Letter</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"https://ilcm.org/images/stories/file_icon.gif\" alt=\"[file]\" border=\"0\" /><a href=\"https://ilcm.org/probono/manuals/DREAMers/ReceiptreceivedLTbilingual.docx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"alternate\">Filing Receipt Letter</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"https://ilcm.org/images/stories/file_icon.gif\" alt=\"[file]\" border=\"0\" /><a href=\"https://ilcm.org/probono/ASCFingerprintLetterBilingual.docx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"alternate\">Fingerprint Appointment Letter</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"https://ilcm.org/images/stories/file_icon.gif\" alt=\"[file]\" border=\"0\" /><a href=\"https://ilcm.org/probono/manuals/DACA_Closing_Letter_English.docx\" targe